reviews.author: David Bray
reviews.text: Was fine. Checked the box for going to the beach in Lima. Beach had sand, which was good because beaches just up the road were only rocks. It also has umbrellas and chairs to rent, which is also nice since other beaches didn‚Äôt look to have that available. We got one umbrella and four chairs for 30 soles, probably could have negotiated lower sine the beach wasn‚Äôt busy at 10am. It was fairly clean, only a little bit of junk that washed ashore or was left behind. There were ‚Äúdrifter‚Äù people packing up their camp and washing themselves in the water when we arrived. They didn‚Äôt make a show of it so it wasn‚Äôt a huge deal. There were portable toilets that were locked, we didn‚Äôt use them but I‚Äôm assuming we would have had to pay someone to open it for us. All in all, it was just fine. Definitely been to better beaches in the world but deemed good for Lima.

During our visit to Playa Barrancos, we took the opportunity to walk along the malec√≥n all the way back to our hotel. The path is quite suitable for a leisurely stroll, though it‚Äôs worth noting that some parts of the walkway could benefit from better maintenance and cleaning.

Despite this, sitting by the shore to watch the sunset proved to be a memorable experience. The view of surfers riding the waves as the sun dipped below the horizon was truly captivating. While Playa Barrancos may not be the cleanest beach, it certainly has its moments of beauty, especially during the evening. It‚Äôs a great spot for those looking to relax and enjoy some natural coastal charm.
